### C-4: CTA Label Inconsistency Creates Decision Fatigue

**Problem:** The page currently has **10+ distinct CTA labels** across sections:

| Location | Label |
|---|---|
| Hero | "Get a Free Quote" |
| Hero | "Call Now: (512)..." |
| Service cards (×5) | "Quote This Service →" |
| Industries header | "Talk Through Your Scope →" |
| Industry cards (×3) | "Discuss Your Project →" |
| Service Area | "Check Availability in Your Area →" |
| About | "Start Your Project →" |
| Quote section form | "Submit Quote Request" |
| Quote section below | "Prefer to call?" |
| Footer banner | "Get Your Free Quote" |
| Sticky bar | "Free Quote" / "Call" |

That's **13 different CTA labels** leading to essentially the same action (open quote form or call). On mobile, where every scroll-height matters, this creates decision fatigue and dilutes urgency. The user doesn't know which one is "the real one."

**What top sites do:** 2–3 CTA labels max, used consistently:
- **Primary:** "Get a Free Quote" (everywhere it appears)
- **Secondary:** "Call Now" (phone action)
- **Contextual variation:** Only when genuinely different (e.g., "See Open Positions" for careers)

**Recommended approach:**
- Standardize on **"Get a Free Quote"** for all quote-opening CTAs
- Standardize on **"Call Now"** for all phone CTAs
- Remove the "Learn More About Us" CTA below the quote form (sends users *away* from conversion)
- Keep only genuinely different CTAs: "See Open Positions" (careers), "See the Difference" (B&A)

**Impact:** Reduces cognitive load, strengthens brand consistency, improves conversion clarity. This aligns with F-25 (CTA Taxonomy) from the feature roadmap.

**Effort:** Small (1–2 hours). Copy changes across components.

