### R-5: Intersection Observer Proliferation

Current observer count on a full page render:

| Source | Count |
|---|---|
| `AuthorityBar` | 1 |
| `ServiceSpreadSection` (5 items) | 5 |
| `OfferAndIndustrySection` | 1 |
| `BeforeAfterSlider` | 1 |
| `TestimonialSection` | 1 |
| `TimelineSection` (1 parent + 4 steps) | 5 |
| `AboutSection` (3+ ScrollReveal instances) | 3+ |
| `CareersSection` (4+ ScrollReveal instances) | 4+ |
| `ServiceAreaSection` | 1 |
| `QuoteSection` | 1 |
| **Total** | **~23+** |

Each `useInViewOnce` and `ScrollReveal` creates its own `IntersectionObserver`. Modern browsers handle this fine, but 23+ observers is excessive.

**Recommendation for post-launch:** Create a shared `IntersectionObserver` manager that registers all elements on a single observer with a callback map. Standard pattern:

```tsx
// Shared singleton observer
const observerCallbacks = new Map<Element, () => void>();
const sharedObserver = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {
  entries.forEach(entry => {
    if (entry.isIntersecting) {
      observerCallbacks.get(entry.target)?.();
      sharedObserver.unobserve(entry.target);
      observerCallbacks.delete(entry.target);
    }
  });
}, { threshold: 0.15 });
```

**Flag for post-launch. Not blocking.**

